Tidyverse: ggplot

Bernard Ade

ggplot is a powerful data visualization library created by Hadley Wickham. gglot is based on the grammar of graphics which outlines a universal grammar to build plots. This post picks up where the previous post about dplyr ended. I will demonstate the power of combining dplyr and ggplot to create insightful graphs.

library(dplyr)
library(ggplot2)
library(lubridate)
library(scales)
superstore = read.csv('superstore.csv')
superstore = superstore %>% mutate(`Order.Date` = mdy(`Order.Date`))
superstore = superstore %>% mutate(`Ship.Date` = mdy(`Ship.Date`))
superstore

Line graph

Basic line graph showing sum of sales by year.

superstore %>% 
  mutate(year = year(Order.Date)) %>% 
  group_by(year) %>% 
  summarise(sum = sum(Sales)) %>%
  ggplot(aes(x = year, y = sum)) + geom_line() + scale_y_continuous(labels = dollar) +
  xlab("Year") + ylab("Sum of Sales")

Bar plot

Basic bar graph showing sum of sales by year.

superstore %>% 
  mutate(year = year(Order.Date)) %>% 
  group_by(year) %>% 
  summarise(sum = sum(Sales)) %>%
  ggplot(aes(x = year, y = sum)) + geom_bar(stat = "identity") + scale_y_continuous(labels = dollar)

Area Chart

Basic area graph showing sum of sales by year.

superstore %>%
  mutate(year = year(Order.Date)) %>% 
  group_by(year, Region) %>% 
  summarise(sum = sum(Sales)) %>%
  ggplot(aes(x = year, y = sum, fill = Region)) + geom_area() + scale_y_continuous(labels = dollar) + xlab("Year") + ylab("Sum of Sales")

Scatter Plot

Basic scatter plot showing relationship between Sales and Profit.

superstore %>%
  ggplot(aes(Sales, Profit)) + geom_point() + scale_y_continuous(labels = dollar) +   scale_x_continuous(labels = dollar)

Adding a smooth line to previous scatter plot.

superstore %>%
  ggplot(aes(Sales, Profit)) + geom_point() + scale_y_continuous(labels = dollar) +   scale_x_continuous(labels = dollar) + geom_smooth()

Histogram

Histogram showing count of quantity.

superstore %>% 
  ggplot(aes(Quantity)) + geom_histogram()

Boxplot

Basic barplot charting discount by category.

superstore %>%
  ggplot(aes(x = Category, y = Discount)) + geom_boxplot() + scale_y_continuous(labels = percent)

Faceting

Faceting divides plots into a matrix of panels. Sales by Region.

superstore %>%
  mutate(date = year(Order.Date))%>%
  group_by(date, Region) %>% 
  summarise(sum = sum(Sales)) %>%
  ggplot(aes(x = date, y = sum))+ geom_line() +
   facet_wrap(~Region) + xlab("Year") + ylab("Sum of Sales")
